677
74:43.920 --> 74:53.340
The idea is that if we
have some other string that isn't the all-zero
vector and it isn't s, then each one of the random
strings, y1 through yk,

678
74:53.340 --> 74:58.470
is basically going to knock
it out of the null space with probability a half.

679
74:58.470 --> 75:05.670
So after k shots, it's not
at all likely to survive, and in fact, none of the
strings that don't belong

680
75:05.670 --> 75:14.760
are likely to survive. And a very simple fact
from probability theory, known as the union bound, can
be used to establish that.

681
75:14.760 --> 75:22.710
I haven't explained all
of the details here, but hopefully, you get the idea that by computing the null
space modulo-2 of this matrix m,

682
75:22.710 --> 75:30.630
we are very likely to recover s, and that's how Simon's algorithm
solves Simon's problem.

683
75:30.630 --> 75:38.490
There's just one thing left
to say about Simon's problem, and it concerns the classical
difficulty of this problem,

684
75:38.490 --> 75:45.630
that is, how many queries does a classical query algorithm need to solve Simon's problem?

685
75:45.630 --> 75:49.380
The answer is, a lot, in general.

686
75:49.380 --> 76:00.810
There are different precise
statements that can be made about the classical
difficulty of this problem, and here's just one of them.

687
76:00.810 --> 76:10.110
If we have any probabilistic
query algorithm and that algorithm makes fewer than 2 to the power n over 2
minus 1, minus 1 queries,

688
76:10.110 --> 76:16.680
so that's a number of queries
that's exponential in n, then that algorithm will fail
to solve Simon's problem,

689
76:16.680 --> 76:20.280
with probability at least a half.

690
76:20.280 --> 76:27.090
Sometimes, proving
impossibility results like this can be very challenging, but this one isn't too difficult to prove

691
76:27.090 --> 76:31.260
through an elementary
probabilistic analysis.

692
76:31.260 --> 76:37.920
I won't do that in this video lesson, and I'll just instead focus
on the intuition behind it.

693
76:37.920 --> 76:46.290
We're trying to find the hidden string s, but so long as we don't query the function on two strings having
the same output value,

694
76:46.290 --> 76:50.010
we'll get very limited
information about s.

695
76:50.010 --> 76:59.040
Basically, all we learn is
that the hidden string s is not the eXclusive OR of any two distinct
strings that we've queried,

696
76:59.040 --> 77:05.790
And if we query the function at fewer than this number of queries, there will still be a lot of choices of s

697
77:05.790 --> 77:08.790
that haven't been ruled out.

698
77:08.790 --> 77:13.050
This isn't a formal proof,
but that is the basic idea.

699
77:13.050 --> 77:22.980
So in summary, Simon's algorithm provides us with a striking advantage of quantum over classical
algorithms within the query model.

700
77:22.980 --> 77:32.580
In particular, Simon's
algorithm solves Simon's problem with a number of queries that's linear in the number of input
bits n to our function,

701
77:32.580 --> 77:39.900
whereas any classical algorithm,
even if it's probabilistic, needs to make a number of
queries that's exponential in n

702
77:39.900 --> 77:46.830
in order to solve Simon's problem with a reasonable probability of success.

703
77:46.830 --> 77:54.540
It's true that Simon's problem is a somewhat artificial problem that presumably nobody
really wants to solve,

704
77:54.540 --> 78:01.650
but that's secondary. Sometimes ideas need to be developed before they're put into practice.

705
78:01.650 --> 78:09.030
And indeed, Peter Shor has clearly stated that it was Simon's algorithm that inspired his now
famous quantum algorithm

706
78:09.030 --> 78:14.010
for integer factorization, which we'll see in a couple of lessons.

707
78:14.010 --> 78:17.340
And that is the end of Lesson 5.

708
78:17.340 --> 78:23.370
In this lesson, we've taken a look at the
query model of computation, and we've seen a progression of examples

709
78:23.370 --> 78:30.240
of quantum algorithms
that exhibit advantages over classical algorithms
within this model.

710
78:30.240 --> 78:36.990
There is, in fact, a lot more
known about the query model and quantum algorithms for other problems that
I've not discussed.

711
78:36.990 --> 78:43.320
So if you find this
model to be interesting, there's quite a lot
more to learn about it.

712
78:43.320 --> 78:50.190
Our next step will be to move
away from the query model and toward a model of computation
that's more representative

713
78:50.190 --> 78:55.560
of the sorts of problems that we might hope to solve in practice.

714
78:55.560 --> 79:03.060
I hope you'll join me for Lesson 6, where will focus mainly on
laying down a foundation for studying quantum algorithms.

715
79:03.060 --> 79:09.630
And from there, we'll move on to some
specific quantum algorithms, including Shor's algorithm
for integer factorization

716
79:09.630 --> 79:12.663
in subsequent lessons. Goodbye until then!
